00:19:53.814 --> 00:19:56.650 align:middle line:84%
>>And that's why
we must go there.

00:19:56.650 --> 00:19:59.770 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Post-humanity, the
end of the world, "Manhattan."

00:19:59.770 --> 00:20:00.570 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: Yep.

00:20:00.570 --> 00:20:01.710 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: And we
know that Manhattan

00:20:01.710 --> 00:20:03.000 align:middle line:90%
has been completely destroyed.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:04.560 align:middle line:90%
It's flooded.

00:20:04.560 --> 00:20:08.160 align:middle line:84%
So what is fascinating about
this scene on many levels

00:20:08.160 --> 00:20:12.470 align:middle line:84%
is I noticed the
playing with language.

00:20:12.470 --> 00:20:14.220 align:middle line:84%
So Spielberg does this
a lot in his films,

00:20:14.220 --> 00:20:18.240 align:middle line:84%
and we mentioned earlier the
cabalistic ideas of Hebrew

00:20:18.240 --> 00:20:21.630 align:middle line:84%
vowels and making something
come alive, a golem, basically,

00:20:21.630 --> 00:20:23.257 align:middle line:90%
with the imprinting protocol.

00:20:23.257 --> 00:20:24.840 align:middle line:84%
But if you've seen
"Close Encounters,"

00:20:24.840 --> 00:20:26.670 align:middle line:84%
that whole film is
actually about language

00:20:26.670 --> 00:20:27.750 align:middle line:90%
and communication.

00:20:27.750 --> 00:20:29.190 align:middle line:90%
So is "ET," by the way.

00:20:29.190 --> 00:20:31.720 align:middle line:84%
It's all about how do we
communicate across cultures,

00:20:31.720 --> 00:20:35.580 align:middle line:84%
across spiritual boundaries
and planes, perhaps.

00:20:35.580 --> 00:20:38.760 align:middle line:84%
But in this, it's bots
communicating with bot.

00:20:38.760 --> 00:20:42.330 align:middle line:84%
I like that he combines
these seemingly two disparate

00:20:42.330 --> 00:20:45.990 align:middle line:84%
impossible categories of a
flat fact with a fairytale,

00:20:45.990 --> 00:20:48.280 align:middle line:84%
and this basically
melts down Google.

00:20:48.280 --> 00:20:50.400 align:middle line:84%
It goes into
shutdown mode, and it

00:20:50.400 --> 00:20:53.250 align:middle line:84%
triggers this alternate
program to come up

00:20:53.250 --> 00:20:57.180 align:middle line:84%
that is the clue from Dr.
Hobby to lead David back

00:20:57.180 --> 00:21:00.180 align:middle line:84%
to self-discovery, his
origins, his creator,

00:21:00.180 --> 00:21:03.330 align:middle line:84%
and, again, we're going to find
out that this human creator is

00:21:03.330 --> 00:21:04.710 align:middle line:90%
less than ideal.

00:21:04.710 --> 00:21:05.660 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: Yeah.

00:21:05.660 --> 00:21:09.240 align:middle line:84%
It was a test by Dr.
Hobby to find out

00:21:09.240 --> 00:21:12.960 align:middle line:84%
which robot would figure out
its own sentience first and come

00:21:12.960 --> 00:21:14.520 align:middle line:90%
back to meet its master.

00:21:14.520 --> 00:21:18.120 align:middle line:84%
And again, very close to
Decker in "Blade Runner"

00:21:18.120 --> 00:21:20.340 align:middle line:90%
and various other films, too.

00:21:20.340 --> 00:21:22.950 align:middle line:84%
So again, this is
the constant theme

00:21:22.950 --> 00:21:27.360 align:middle line:84%
within the alchemical myths
of creating life and having

00:21:27.360 --> 00:21:29.160 align:middle line:90%
it come back to its creator.

00:21:29.160 --> 00:21:31.170 align:middle line:84%
In this instance,
Spielberg doesn't

00:21:31.170 --> 00:21:34.470 align:middle line:84%
have to kill its
creator, but it's still

00:21:34.470 --> 00:21:36.204 align:middle line:90%
kind of an amazing scene.

00:21:36.204 --> 00:21:38.370 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Well, when we think
about "Dante's Inferno,"

00:21:38.370 --> 00:21:44.340 align:middle line:84%
again, after this scene is when
