00:26:49.950 --> 00:26:52.050 align:middle line:90%
They know what you want to buy.

00:26:52.050 --> 00:26:54.000 align:middle line:84%
They know what kind
of clothes you want.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:55.700 align:middle line:90%
That's pretty shaky.

00:26:55.700 --> 00:26:58.880 align:middle line:84%
And now, of course,
with Google, you

00:26:58.880 --> 00:27:02.720 align:middle line:84%
can say a word in your
office of a product

00:27:02.720 --> 00:27:05.959 align:middle line:84%
that you're interested in,
and you open up your computer,

00:27:05.959 --> 00:27:07.750 align:middle line:84%
and they've already
heard it, processed it.

00:27:07.750 --> 00:27:11.390 align:middle line:84%
Now, you're getting cookies
downloading on whatever product

00:27:11.390 --> 00:27:14.990 align:middle line:84%
you were talking about, not
searching for on Google,

00:27:14.990 --> 00:27:18.350 align:middle line:84%
but literally talking when
you think the computer is off.

00:27:18.350 --> 00:27:20.390 align:middle line:84%
That's actually
happened to me recently.

00:27:20.390 --> 00:27:23.157 align:middle line:84%
So that's another thing about
this movie that is amazing.

00:27:23.157 --> 00:27:25.490 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Yeah, the predictive
programming is fascinating.

00:27:25.490 --> 00:27:29.900 align:middle line:84%
In fact, I usually say
that what you see in a film

00:27:29.900 --> 00:27:32.420 align:middle line:84%
